s 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaune","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Dietmar, Erwin, Fritz, Siegfried.","German: variant of   Braun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Braun","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Ernst, Otto, Alois, Gerhard, Helmut, Fritz, Heinz, Joerg, Wolfgang, Egon.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname from German <i>braun</i> ‘brown’ (Middle High German <i>brūn</i>), referring to the color of the hair, complexion, or clothing.","German: from the personal name <i>Bruno</i>, which was borne by the Dukes of Saxony, among others, from the 10th century or before. It was also the name of several medieval German and Italian saints, including Saint Bruno, the founder of the Carthusian order (1030–1101), who was born in Cologne. See also   Brun  ."]}]},{"name":"Lucie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin.  See  <b>Lucy</b>   . This has now largely replaced the older French form  Luce ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lucie de Beaune was born in 1075, her father, Thibaut de Beaune Vicomte de Dijon, was 31 and her mother, Lucie de Dijon-Nacot, was 20. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Gosbert de la Ferté. She died in 1127, in La Ferté-Ma